{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479090"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:20:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:20:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19193"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19193"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.08,0.83,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81955"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11927"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67225"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"130"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"},{"type":"tags","id":"8219"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27945"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81955"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-month history of headaches and dizziness. He has lost 3 kg in weight despite a good appetite. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His parent has recently been diagnosed with medullary thyroid cancer. On examination, he appears anxious. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 190/140 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His heart sounds are normal and there are no abdominal masses. Fundoscopy reveals grade II hypertensive retinopathy. His 24-hour urinary normetanephrine is 1200 nmol/day (100-500). CT imaging shows bilateral adrenal masses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying genetic condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tuberous sclerosis","Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome","Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2A","Neurofibromatosis type 1","Succinate dehydrogenase deficiency syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of pheochromocytoma including sustained hypertension, headaches, weight loss despite good appetite, and elevated urinary normetanephrine. The family history of medullary thyroid cancer and bilateral adrenal masses strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple endocrine neoplasia type 2A (MEN2A)\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon Hippel-Lindau syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can also present with bilateral pheochromocytomas but typically includes other features such as retinal hemangioblastomas and renal cell carcinomas. There is also no family history suggestive of VHL.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurofibromatosis type 1\u003C/strong\u003E can be associated with pheochromocytoma but would typically present with caf\u00e9-au-lait spots and other cutaneous manifestations, which are not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberous sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E rarely causes pheochromocytoma and would typically present with other features such as seizures, developmental delay, and characteristic skin lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuccinate dehydrogenase deficiency syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with paragangliomas and pheochromocytomas but these are more commonly extraadrenal and malignant, unlike the bilateral adrenal masses seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMEN2A is caused by mutations in the RET proto-oncogene and is characterised by medullary thyroid carcinoma (as seen in the parent), pheochromocytoma (approximately 50% of cases), and hyperparathyroidism. The presence of bilateral adrenal masses in a child with a family history of medullary thyroid cancer makes this the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pheochromocytoma in children typically presents with sustained rather than paroxysmal hypertension.","Children with pheochromocytoma predominantly excrete norepinephrine rather than epinephrine.","Over 20% of childhood pheochromocytomas are bilateral and 30-40% have extraadrenal involvement."],"references":["Kliegman RM, St. Geme JW, Blum NJ, Shah SS, Tasker RC, Wilson KM, editors. Pheochromocytoma. In: Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. 21st ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67225"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19193"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67225"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T13:42:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T13:43:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11927"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81955"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"ta